Bad Movie?
The most ambitious crossover event since 2018.

Author: Jake Mraz

Introduction¶

In this tutorial I will be examining one of my favorite things, movies. For a while now I have been able to watch a movie trailer and predict if the movie would do well or not, like calling that Ghostbusters was going to be awful or that Batman the Dark Knight would be awesome. While I had these feelings, I wondered if I could prove this with data. So for this I will be examining if it is possible to predict a movies success, or better yet, will a movie fail?
Of course we first need to explain what a failure is to a movie. A naturally simple way to define this is a movie which loses money. Defining a success is a little more tricky since there is no definitive point where a movie can be considered success, but we also know we would not consider a movie a complete failure if it were able to cover loss. Since I will be dealing mostly with prediciting if a movie will fail, and defining success is mostly subjective, I will leave this definition up to you.

We are going to begin by importing the movie data. I recieved my data from separate sources and because of this, I need both files to gather the data I need from each source. During this section I will be focused on condesning the data down and lining up all IDs to make moving between various datasources easier.
You will notice some similarities between the datasets, this is because the data which will be put into movies_df is based off of the data from MovieLens, but examines some parts further while ignoring other parts. Below you can find links to the data. I will also include the links used throughout this tutorial in a section at the bottom.
Kaggle Movies Data: https://www.kaggle.com/rounakbanik/the-movies-dataset variables dealing with this data will begin with a 'k'
MovieLens Data: https://grouplens.org/datasets/movielens/latest/ variables dealing with this data will begin with 'm'

While we might not have that many movies, we have over 50 million combined ratings, and about 15 million scores. I will explain exactly what the scores are in a later section when we begin to work with them, but they help to identify which tags are relevant to each movie. I will include this link when we go more into it, but if you would like to read more about Tag Genomes, http://files.grouplens.org/papers/tag_genome.pdf this article provides plenty of information. The ratings are stored as one user rating one movie, and these ratings will be necessary later.
Due to the large amount of data, we will be working with a smaller sample. Before we can trim data, we need to figure out exactly what we are going to be looking at. All the columns I will be taking mean exactly what one would expect, and id is used in reference to some of the other tables, with the exception of status, which represents if the movie was realeased or not.

#I begin by importing datetime to help evaluate the year it was released
from datetime import datetime

for index, date in k_movies_df.iterrows():
    #Using try catch in case the value is not formatted correctly
    try:
        time = datetime.strptime(date['release_date'], '%Y-%m-%d')
        if time.year <= 2010 or time.year >= 2015:
             k_movies_df.drop(index=index, inplace=True) 
        continue
            
    except:
        k_movies_df.drop(index=index, inplace=True)

Now we are starting to get a number we can work with. Whehn we review the result, we see that some movies have not budget, so they cannot fail by our definition. This may be a situtation where some a kid name Billy takes a video camera and makes his own movie, which centainly does not belong in the same catagory as a movie like Limitless. To prevent these from skewing the data we will remove all movies with a budget uner 100,000. (Just in case Billy also took his dad's money)

In [9]:
for index, budget in k_movies_df.iterrows():
    cutoffbudget = 100000 
    #Stored as a string so we will cast to int to make comparison
    if int(budget['budget']) <= cutoffbudget:
         k_movies_df.drop(index=index, inplace=True)

2. Recap of Section 1¶

We are going to be looking at movies with a minimum budget of $100,000, earned revenue, and were released between 2010 and 2015.
For these movies were have the following information:

  • Genre _ Ratings
  • Budget
  • Revenue
  • Tags describing movie
  • Relevance of those tags
  • Release Date

3. Is there a coorelation between ratings and profit?¶

We will begin by getting the ratings of the movies we are going to be looking at. The ratings dataframe stores a value everytime a user rates a movie. To get a movies rating we will simply average all the ratings it has received. We will compare this rating to the percentage of profit the movie made. Will this be a valid way of predicting a movies success I wonder?
*You will need following imports for this section

In [17]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

l = k_ratings_df.groupby('movieId')
k_rated = []
percents = []
num = 0
for index, mId in k_movies_df_abr.iterrows():
    try:
        percent = (int(mId['revenue']) - int(mId['budget']))/int(mId['budget'])
        #Notcied 2 outliers so this it to remove them
        if percent > 18:
            continue
        else:
            k_rated.append(l.get_group(int(mId['id']))['rating'].mean())
            percents.append(percent)
    except:
        continue

Before we continue, I will first state that to begin, we will assume that there is no correlation between ratings and percent of budget earned (as profit) or lost, ie a correlation coefficient of 0. We will be using a typical significance value of .05.

Well .14 is greater than our significance value, so we will reject the null hypothesis. I was hoping for a larger correlation in hopes that by prediciting ratings we could also predict success, but I will explore other possibilities.

4. Exploring Data¶

In this section we will be looking into using the top three tags in conjuction with the genre of the movie to see if we can predict if it will fail.

tester = k_movies_df_abr
for index, mId in tester.iterrows():

    if(int(mId['revenue']) - int(mId['budget']) > 0):
        result = 1
    else:
        result = 0

In [22]:
mix_df = {'title':[],'movieId':[],'genres':[],'budget':[],'fail':[]}

    #ensure all our data has genres and removing duplicates
    if(row['genres'] != '(no genres listed)' and not (title in mix_df['title'])):

tag_df = {'title':[],'movieId':[],'genres':[],'budget':[],'fail':[],'tag':[]}
for index, row in three_genre_df.iterrows():
    title = row['title']
    for t in row['tags']:
        tag_df['tag'].append(t)
        tag_df['title'].append(row['title'])
        tag_df['movieId'].append(int(row['movieId']))
        tag_df['budget'].append(int(row['budget']))
        tag_df['fail'].append(int(row['fail']))
        tag_df['genres'].append(row['genres'])

from sklearn import model_selection

#breaking up the dataframe for testing purposes
train = final_df[0:1500]

feats = ['budget','num_genre','num_tag']

X = features

clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier()
clf = clf.fit(X,y)

In [52]:
test['predictions'] = preds
grouped_test = test.groupby('title')


together_again = {'title':[],'actual':[],'prediction':[]}

for name, row in grouped_test:
    if(1 in row['fail'].values):
        actual = 1
    else:
        actual = 0
    total = 0
    pred_total = 0
    for index, stuff in row.iterrows():
        pred_total = pred_total + stuff['predictions']
        total = total+1
    if(float(total/2) < float(pred_total)):
        final_prediction = 1
    else:
        final_prediction = 0
    
    together_again['title'].append(name)
    together_again['actual'].append(actual)
    together_again['prediction'].append(final_prediction)
    
final_results_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(together_again)
accuracy_score(final_results_df['actual'].values, final_results_df['prediction'].values)
